We have approximately – going through all the cost cuts through Q1 – we have approximately $100 million a quarter more of cost cuts that are going to come through the Eastern Hemisphere and also Latin America. But that is actually – but a lot of it is going to come through the Eastern Hemisphere. That is quite a cushion on further erosion coming from volumes and pricing.
The second thing also, Bill, is that when we talk about product sales, that is one we have some visibility on. We have a notion of what is going to be delivered or expected to be delivered in a number of different products, and that gives us also a sense of volume and margins to come. The services more, I think – I think are vulnerable in the event the project gets further canceled and so forth. Respect to pricing, we also have in a sense what was given. In our particular case, pricing concessions have been given. There is no significant amounts of other pricing concessions being negotiated for us. I'll also point out to you that there are very large tender activities which are ongoing which have been very recent, which suggests that many of our clients all the sudden are very interested in locking in volumes at current pricing, which suggests also that volume is unlikely to go down further, more likely to inch up some.
All this would tell you that the cost reductions are sizable, the product line deliveries are relatively predictable, pricing concessions we have already, quite a bit, have gone through Q4 and Q1 here now. There isn't much that we know of analytically to go through incrementally in Q2. All of this to say that the road map for international in Q2, Q3, Q4, should be, depending on your viewpoint on the macro, either constructive or better than constructive in our particular case.
