Rob J. MacKenzie - IBERIA Capital Partners LLC
Thanks, guys. Bernard, a couple questions for you, if I may. First, are you guys seeing any signs of pickup, say, in the U.S. in any kind of completions or workover activity for you guys? And, secondly, as part of your conversations with your customers that you talked about earlier, how have those changed, if you will, over the past week, two weeks, month, two months? Are we seeing a turn in sentiment there?
Bernard J. Duroc-Danner - Chairman, President & Chief Executive Officer
Okay. On the first one, I'm sorry to say, that, no, there isn't any signs of a pickup or anything else like that as of today in the U.S. – i.e., I think the U.S., it's really a question of cash flow for our clients. And that's price of oil, and it's also financing capabilities. This is one thing.
The second is interesting question. It's very simple. I'm getting a lot of questions on what I am seeing in terms of production rate difficulties with other reservoirs and other plays from particular clients wanting to know how the other ones are doing, what do I see in terms of trends. It's sort of interesting that they want to compare their own difficulties on and around decline rates with other difficulties, not so much for competitive reasons, but to get a sense what is happening to the industry.
There's been a real lot – these are informal conversations. They are outside of the realm of formal meetings which take place also with clients. And I think, for me, are far more valuable than the formal aspects. So it's a lot of conversations, systematically, really, from what am I seeing in other parts of the world. One of the advantages of being an oilfield service person, from an oil and gas perspective, is you get to see lots of reservoirs and lots of reservoir situations, actually more so than the people exploiting it, who are constrained or restricted to the ones they're developing. You have a rich sort of pool of information as, if you will, a traveling salesman, as it were.
Rob J. MacKenzie - IBERIA Capital Partners LLC
Great. Thank you. But in terms of what they're indicating to you – I understand that they're pumping you for information, but what are they indicating to you, if anything, about how their plans are evolving?

Bernard J. Duroc-Danner - Chairman, President & Chief Executive Officer
They are sort of – in general, they have no authority or capital or plans for additional drilling, and they're trying to hold off decline rates. And they are, in many cases, it's coming to the point where they cannot do that anymore and so it creates a lot of strain and worries, and they're quite anxious to know where and when cash flow will allow them to restart activity, because they're very afraid of losing production rather rapidly now. There is an acceleration. You hold it off and ultimately there is acceleration.
Rob J. MacKenzie - IBERIA Capital Partners LLC
Great...
Bernard J. Duroc-Danner - Chairman, President & Chief Executive Officer
So there's really a sense of – we're at the point now where they are afraid of declines that they cannot hold off, hence their interest in understanding where and when the industry could have a turn because they're sort of worried about their own production profile, given the fact they're running out of – through intervention and the sorts of things you can do with a limited budget, very, very scarce drilling, they're worried about being able to hold off the decline rates where they are without them accelerating further.
Rob J. MacKenzie - IBERIA Capital Partners LLC
That's very helpful. Thank you.
Bernard J. Duroc-Danner - Chairman, President & Chief Executive Officer
Thank you.
